(41, 8, 32, 41, 4, 38, 38, NULL, 'Disciples'' Concern for Jesus', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' concern for Jesus'' awareness of their peril. In both passages, Peter and the disciples express a sense of urgency and fear regarding their situation, questioning Jesus'' attention to their plight.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 8, 32, 42, 10, 40, 40, NULL, 'Concern for Service and Duty', 'This connection highlights the theme of concern for responsibilities and roles. In Mark, Peter''s rebuke reflects a misunderstanding of Jesus'' mission, while in Luke, Martha''s complaint reveals her frustration over her sister''s lack of participation in serving.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 8, 33, 40, 4, 10, 10, 'Get thee behind me, Satan', 'Rebuke of Satan Connection', 'This connection highlights the use of the phrase ''Get thee hence, Satan'' in both passages, where Jesus rebukes influences that oppose God''s will. Both instances emphasize the conflict between divine purpose and human understanding.', 'keyword', 0.356, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 8, 33, 50, 3, 19, 19, 'savourest not the things that be of God', 'Focus on Earthly vs. Divine', 'This connection highlights the contrast between valuing earthly things and divine priorities. Both passages emphasize the danger of prioritizing human desires over God''s will.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 8, 33, 62, 2, 15, 15, 'savourest not the things that be of God', 'Worldly vs. Divine Values', 'This connection highlights the contrast between valuing worldly things and valuing the things of God. Both passages emphasize the importance of aligning one''s priorities with divine will rather than human desires.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 8, 33, 59, 3, 15, 18, 'savourest not the things that be of God', 'Wisdom and Human Understanding', 'This connection highlights the contrast between earthly wisdom and divine understanding. In Mark, Peter''s focus on human concerns is rebuked, paralleling James'' description of earthly wisdom as ''devilish'' and ''sensual.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 8, 33, 1, 3, 4, 6, 'savourest not the things that be of God', 'Temptation and Human Perspective', 'This connection highlights the theme of human perspective versus divine will. In Mark, Peter''s focus on human concerns is rebuked, paralleling the serpent''s temptation in Genesis that appeals to human desires and wisdom.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 8, 33, 19, 141, 5, 5, 'Get thee behind me, Satan', 'Rebuke and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of rebuke as a form of kindness. Both passages emphasize the value of correction, with Mark 8:33 illustrating the necessity of discerning God''s will over human desires, while Psalms 141:5 presents righteous rebuke as beneficial.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
